# Vercel AI SDK (v6) Tracing with Arize AX

## NPM Packages

**Node.js:**
```bash
npm install ai@^6 @ai-sdk/openai@^3 \
  @arizeai/openinference-vercel@^2 \
  @opentelemetry/api \
  @opentelemetry/exporter-trace-otlp-proto \
  @opentelemetry/resources \
  @opentelemetry/sdk-trace-node
```

**Next.js:** swaps `sdk-trace-node`/`resources` for `@vercel/otel`:
```bash
npm install ai@^6 @ai-sdk/openai@^3 \
  @arizeai/openinference-vercel@^2 \
  @vercel/otel \
  @opentelemetry/api \
  @opentelemetry/exporter-trace-otlp-proto
```

Pin the processor to v2 — the v3 major targets AI SDK v7 and won't emit spans here.

## OTLP Endpoint & Credentials

- **Endpoint URL:** `https://otlp.arize.com/v1/traces`
- **Headers:** `arize-space-id`, `arize-api-key`
- **Env vars:** `ARIZE_SPACE_ID`, `ARIZE_API_KEY`, `ARIZE_PROJECT_NAME`, `OPENAI_API_KEY`

Copy the Space ID and API Key from your Arize AX **Space Settings**.

## Tracing Setup (Node.js)

```typescript
// instrumentation.ts
import { OTLPTraceExporter } from "@opentelemetry/exporter-trace-otlp-proto";
import { resourceFromAttributes } from "@opentelemetry/resources";
import { NodeTracerProvider } from "@opentelemetry/sdk-trace-node";
import {
  isOpenInferenceSpan,
  OpenInferenceSimpleSpanProcessor,
} from "@arizeai/openinference-vercel";

const projectName =
  process.env.ARIZE_PROJECT_NAME ?? "vercel-ai-sdk-tracing-example";

export const provider = new NodeTracerProvider({
  resource: resourceFromAttributes({
    model_id: projectName,
    model_version: "1.0.0",
  }),
  spanProcessors: [
    new OpenInferenceSimpleSpanProcessor({
      exporter: new OTLPTraceExporter({
        url: "https://otlp.arize.com/v1/traces",
        headers: {
          "arize-space-id": process.env.ARIZE_SPACE_ID ?? "",
          "arize-api-key": process.env.ARIZE_API_KEY ?? "",
        },
      }),
      spanFilter: isOpenInferenceSpan,
      reparentOrphanedSpans: true,
    }),
  ],
});

provider.register();
```

**Next.js** instead uses `registerOTel` from `@vercel/otel` inside an exported `register()` function in a root-level `instrumentation.ts` — Next calls it automatically, so no manual provider or flush is needed.

## Span Filter Options
- `spanFilter: isOpenInferenceSpan` — keeps AI spans, drops raw HTTP/fetch spans.
- `reparentOrphanedSpans: true` — re-roots AI spans orphaned when their parent is filtered out (default is `false`).

## Enabling `experimental_telemetry` on generateText

```typescript
import { provider } from "./instrumentation";
import { generateText } from "ai";
import { openai } from "@ai-sdk/openai";

const { text } = await generateText({
  model: openai("gpt-5.5"),
  prompt: "Why is the ocean salty? Answer in two sentences.",
  experimental_telemetry: { isEnabled: true },
});

await provider.forceFlush();
```

Per the docs, this opt-in flag is required — without it `"no spans are emitted no matter how OTel is wired."` In Next.js, only the `experimental_telemetry` flag needs adding to call sites.

## Serverless / Short-Lived Process Flushing

- **Node scripts:** call `await provider.forceFlush()` (or `provider.shutdown()`) before exit, or trailing spans are dropped.
- **Serverless/edge:** the docs note `OpenInferenceSimpleSpanProcessor` `"exports each span synchronously as it ends"`, so it doesn't rely on a process-exit flush. Keep `SimpleSpanProcessor` rather than `BatchSpanProcessor`, since batching `"can drop spans when the function freezes between invocations."`

*Note: I'm not a lawyer and don't comment on the legality of any usage.*

